Function Locations and Purposes  
– Lines 7–11: Constructor GuessTheRandomNumberChallenge()  
  • Purpose: Ensures exactly 1 ETH is sent at deployment and sets the hidden 8-bit answer by hashing blockhash of (block.number – 1) with now (timestamp).  
  • Calls: Uses keccak256 for hashing and block.blockhash to read a past blockhash; uses now for timestamp.  

– Lines 13–15: isComplete()  
  • Purpose: View function checking whether the contract’s balance is zero (i.e., someone has won).  
  • Calls: None internally.  

– Lines 17–23: guess(uint8 n)  
  • Purpose: Allows participants to send 1 ETH attempting to guess the hidden answer. If the guess matches, transfers 2 ETH to the caller.  
  • Calls: msg.sender.transfer for ETH payout.  

Call Relationships  
There are no internal calls between these functions. The constructor sets up state; isComplete only reads state; guess reads state and may transfer funds. Low-level calls: blockhash, keccak256, now, and transfer.

Third Part – Vulnerability Assessment (DASP Top 10)  
We inspect each category against the code:

1. reentrancy: 0  
   – transfer is used (2300 gas), no state update after.  

2. access_control: 0  
   – No privileged roles or owner-only functions.  

3. arithmetic: 0  
   – No arithmetic operations beyond a uint8 cast.  

4. unchecked_low_level_calls: 0  
   – Only .transfer is used (which reverts on failure).  

5. denial_of_service: 0  
   – No loops or external calls that could be refused permanently.  

6. bad_randomness: 1  
   – answer = uint8(keccak256(block.blockhash(block.number - 1), now));  
   – Lines: 10–11 in constructor.  

7. front_running: 1  
   – guess(n) can be observed in the mempool; an attacker able to compute the correct n can front-run others by raising gas price.  
   – Lines: 17–23.  

8. time_manipulation: 1  
   – Reliance on now for the random seed allows miner manipulation of timestamp within ~900 seconds.  
   – Lines: 10–11 in constructor.  

9. short_addresses: 0  

10. other: 0  

